We recommended that the Management:
Cancel the checks that have become stale totaling P796,381.91 and appropriate payable accounts are to be set-up and cash in bank must be reverted. Payables emanating from stale checks that have been outstanding for 2 ½ years or more from check date may be reverted to unappropriated surplus of the Municipality per Section 98 of PD No. 1445;
Review the reconciling items in the bank reconciliation statements and examine items which have been outstanding for more than one (1) month and prepare journal entries to adjust/correct the book balance;
Advise the claimants of unreleased checks to duly acknowledge the Check Register from the Treasury Office by completely filling out the “Received by” portion including the date when the check was received; and
In preparation to Government Accounting Manual for LGUs, instruct the Treasury Office to prepare and submit a Schedule of Unreleased Checks at year-end to the Accounting Office for the preparation of JEV to restore the cash equivalent of unreleased checks.

We recommended that the Management:
Require the Accountant to submit the details of said accounts in order for the Audit Team to verify the transfers made between the different funds of the Municipality;
Require the Accounting Office to conduct a thorough review of the records aimed at reconciling the reciprocal accounts and determining the cause/s of the difference, and if possible, assign additional personnel to solely man the reconciliation of these accounts on a monthly basis;
Require the Accountant to prepare necessary adjusting entries to bring both accounts into agreement; and
Inform the system provider to address the issue so that the same error will not occur in the future.

We recommended that the Management:
Require the Accounting Unit to practice the imposition of liquidated damages to defaulting suppliers to encourage prompt deliveries of goods to the Municipality and to ensure that all documentary requirements are all in order before processing the disbursement vouchers;
Require the Procuring Office personnel to ensure that all details of the Purchase Orders are provided for proper accountability and transparency;
Require the Supply Officer or authorized personnel to accomplish the Inspection and Acceptance Reports (IARs) completely and properly;
Require the Supply Officer or authorized personnel to ensure that only actual goods delivered are included on the delivery receipts, and subsequent deliveries must be covered with different delivery receipts to reflect the actual flow of goods.  authority is clearly indicated on the space provided for;
Require the Supplier to affix his/her signature over the printed name on the Conforme portion of the PO signifying his/her approval to the term set by the agency/entity and the date of signing;
Direct all suppliers to make deliveries to the Property/Supply Office who shall be accountable and liable for the receipt and inspection of the goods delivered; and
Develop and institute measures to address the lapses on the procurement procedure.

We recommended that on the Credit Memos, Management (1) exert effort through inquiry with the bank to gather information such as what government agency/ies made the deposit/ fund transfer to their account, so that they would recognize whether trust liability or income is to be credited; (2) implement the purpose of the trust receipt according to the terms of the Memorandum of Agreement if the amount pertains to grants by national government agencies; (3) recognize income if the amount refers to revenue subsidy from other government agencies;

On the Debit Memos and unrecorded adjustments, we recommend that Management (1) analyze the cause of the bank charge or deduction from their bank account; (2) prepare the necessary accounting entries to reclassify from Government Equity and hold accountable those persons whose negligence caused the decrease in the municipal bank account by setting up a Receivable from them; (3) prepare necessary entries to record fully identified debit reconciling items or adjustments to properly present their fair value of the Cash in Bank in the financial statements.

On the stale checks, we recommended Management to (1) notify in the form of a confirmation letter to the suppliers/payees concerned of the non-negotiated check still in their custody which were known by Management through the preparation of the bank reconciliation statement, (2) request payees to surrender to the Treasurer the physical check that staled as basis for him to issue replacement check, (3) reverse to unappropriated surplus the payables for the stale check of suppliers not responding within the allowed period of two years since the reversion of these checks into Payables.

In view of the foregoing observations, we recommended that the:
Municipality see to it that the funds allocated for the projects are not utilized beyond its purpose;
Municipality, particularly the MPDC and the Municipal Engineer, (i) see to it that the projects to be charged against the 20 percent DF are feasible for implementation; (ii) prepare the schedule of implementation for the projects which were still not implemented at year-end; (iii) strictly follow the said schedule to avoid incurring delay in the implementation; and (iv) assess the reasons on the construction materials which were still unused for the projects namely: Construction of Apartment-Type Niches and Rehabilitation of Dumpsite and take the necessary actions  in order that the works on these projects be immediately started;
ICO-Municipal Accountant carefully evaluate the status of implementation of continuing projects.  If these were not implemented in the prior year, include those in the List of Vouchers of the current year for proper monitoring; and
Municipal Engineer prepare the Report on PPAs with utmost care to be able to present complete and accurate information to the users thereof.
On the observations pertaining to procurement, we recommended that the BAC:
comply with the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184;
see to it that the information contained in the related documents are consistent; and
submit to the Audit Team the copies of POs and their supporting documents within the period prescribed by COA Circular No. 2009-001.

In view of the foregoing observations, we recommended that the:
GFPS TWG Chairperson and the implementers of the PPAs see to it that the information contained in the GPB and the project proposals are consistent;
GFPS TWG Chairperson facilitate the submission of the lacking documents noted in this report;
implementers of the PPAs ensure that the budgets therefor are utilized for their intended purposes only;
the concerned implementing units, members of the GFPS and the ICO-Municipal Accountant jointly coordinate in the preparation of the Project ARs, GAD AR and the List of Vouchers in order to provide accurate and reliable information therein for the benefit of the users.  They should consider the information contained in the documents attached in the disbursements charged against the GAD PPAs to achieve consistency of information.  Furthermore, they should ensure that the target beneficiaries appearing in the project proposals and project ARs are the same;
ICO-Municipal Accountant ascertain the correctness of the disbursements accounted in the List of Vouchers since this will be used as the basis in the actual expenditures that will be forwarded in the GAD AR; and
BAC see to it that the POs and their supporting documents are submitted to the Audit Team within the period prescribed in COA Circular No. 2009-001.

