We recommended that the: 

SB pass an ordinance for future augmentation of funds to be made;  

Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator, MDRRMO and Municipal Health Officer submit the supplemental AIP approved by the local sanggunian for the COVID-19 PPAs sourced out from the 70% Mitigation Fund for CY 2020, Transportation and Delivery Expenses, Unexpended Balances of LDRRMF of Previous Years, PhilHealth Capitation Fund and OKADA Foundation, Inc., if available.  If not, they should have ensured that the said document has been prepared before the utilization thereof was made since this is a requirement provided in LBC No. 124 and DILG-DBM JMC No. 02; 

MDRRMO and the Municipal Social Welfare and Development Officer, the implementers of the concerned PPAs, submit the distribution sheets for the Audit Team to evaluate whether the food and non-food supplies as well as the multivitamins procured were properly accounted and benefited the residents of the Municipality; 

BAC Chairperson submit an explanation on the procurement timelines undertaken for Project Nos. 9, 16, 17, 25 and 26 which the Audit Team found that the sense of urgency was not properly demonstrated considering that the Procuring Entity adopted the NP-Emergency Cases modality; 

Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant familiarize the provisions of COA Circular No. 2014-002 in the accounting and reporting guidelines of cash donations from local sources; 

Municipal Accountant coordinate with other concerned department heads on the appropriations set aside to finance the COVID-19 PPAs to be able to present accurate information in the Summary of COVID-19 Fund Sources and Utilization.  Consequently, this will help in the determination of correct amount of savings from these PPAs;   

Municipal Accountant completely account the disbursements of COVID-19 PPAs for inclusion in the List of Vouchers which will then be forwarded in the Summary of COVID-19 Fund Sources and Utilization.  This is to be able to provide accurate and reliable information to the users of these documents; and 

LFC comply with the reporting and posting requirements of the Report on Fund Utilization and Status of PPA Imple-mentation.  The LCE is also recommended to notify the other oversight bodies mentioned in DBM LBC No. 125 in the posting of the said report.

We recommended that the: 

MDRRMO evaluate the implementation of the projects classified as CO in a particular year through coordination with other concerned personnel.  If there are projects found to be unimplemented or not yet completed at year-end, include such in the LDRRMFIP on the subsequent year for proper monitoring thereof; 

MDRRMO prepare Revised LDRRMFIP and submit the same to the Audit Team, if necessary; 

SB pass an ordinance for future augmentation of funds to be made;  

MDRRMO see to it that the charges to be made are within the budget limitation of the concerned PPAs to avoid incurring excessive disbursements; 

Municipal Treasurer cause the following fund transfers: (i) an amount of P120,050.00 from the Trust Fund Bank Account No. 1162-1023-69 to the General Fund Bank Account No. 1162-1019-90 for the Procurement of NiEM Kits which was erroneously charged against the latter account; and (ii) an amount of P26,208.08 from the General Fund Bank Account No. 1162-1019-90 to the Trust Fund Bank Account No. 1162-1023-69 representing the adjustments made during the year which should form part of the unexpended balance of 70% Mitigation Fund – MOOE for CY 2019 maintained in the Trust Fund;      

Municipal Treasurer cause a fund transfer amounting to P3,000,000.00 from the General Fund Bank Account No. 1162-1019-90 to Trust Fund Bank Account No. 1162-1023-69.  Thereafter, the Municipal Accountant is recommended to record the receipt thereof in the Trust Liabilities - DRRMF account in compliance with COA Circular No. 2012-002;  

MDRRMO and other end-user units ensure that the items delivered by the suppliers conform with the required technical specifications;  

BAC see to it that the POs and their supporting documents are submitted to the Audit Team within the period prescribed in COA Circular No. 2009-001; and

Municipal Engineer and the MPDC coordinate with the heads of other offices on their projects classified as CO for inclusion in the Quarterly Report on PPAs.

We recommended that the:

MPDC and the Municipal Engineer carefully plan the implementation of the projects charged against the Fund and effectively execute the construction schedule to be able to timely deliver the services to the intended beneficiaries thereof.  They should also take into consideration the procurement timelines to be undertaken thereon in order that the construction materials are completely delivered on the site before the works actually commenced; 

MPDC and the Municipal Engineer submit an explanation on the following: (i) non-implementation of the projects charged against the Fund for CYs 2016, 2019 and 2020; (ii) failure to commence the works on the two projects despite the fact that the materials were already delivered on December 28, 2018; and (iii) implementation of various projects already commenced even before the construction materials procured were delivered by the winning suppliers;

BAC see to it that the POs and their supporting documents are submitted to the Audit Team within the period prescribed in COA Circular No. 2009-001; and

Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Engineer carefully prepare the documents such as the List of Vouchers/Projects for 20% DF and the Report on PPAs by providing complete and accurate information for the benefit of the users thereof.

We recommended that the: 

Municipal Engineer coordinate with the contractor on the submission of the lacking documents noted by the Audit Team; 

Municipal Engineer carefully review the documents submitted by the contractor to be able to present accurate and reliable information to the users thereof; 

Municipal Engineer submit written explanation to support the claim of the contractor and the Management that the actual date of completion is November 30, 2019 considering the information provided by the Audit Team contradicting such claim; and  

Municipal Accountant thoroughly check the completeness of the supporting documents attached to the claims before making payments to the contractor.

We recommended that the: 

LDRRMC (i) carefully prepare the LDRRMFIP in accordance with the relevant provisions of COA Circular No. 2012-002; and (ii) properly classify the projects, programs and activities sourced out from the 70% Mitigation Fund as to MOOE or CO to be able to arrive at the correct amount of the unexpended balance of 70% Mitigation Fund-MOOE that will be transferred to the Special Trust Fund as well as the unexpended balance of 70% Mitigation Fund-CO that will be remained in the General Fund; 

LDRRMO be properly guided by the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 governing the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances to avoid incurring the same lapses in his succeeding official travels;

Municipal Accountant (i) thoroughly evaluate the disbursements to be presented in the List of Vouchers/ Projects Charged Against the Fund since this will be used as the basis in the preparation of the related documents such as Status of DRRMF/QRF and Report on Utilization of DRRMF as well as in the disclosure of the unexpended balance of LDRRMF in the Notes to Financial Statements; (ii) carefully check the completeness of the supporting documents attached to the claims before making payments to the claimants; (iii) make adjustments in the amount of the unexpended balance of 70% Mitigation Fund-MOOE for CY 2019 taking into consideration the transactions which should not have been charged against the Fund; and (iv) properly record the disbursements in their appropriate accounts to correctly present the balances of the affected accounts;

Municipal Engineer and the MPDC submit written explanation on the photographs submitted relative to the payment of wages of laborers for the project – Furnishing and Improvement of Disaster Operation Center funded from the LDRRMF for CY 2017 in order to validate the payment made and the reported accomplish-ments in the Certificate of Inspection for Final Payment;

BAC strictly comply with the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and see to it that copies of POs and their supporting documents are submitted to the Audit Team within the period prescribed by COA Circular No. 2009-001; and

Municipal Accountant and the LDRRMO see to it that all the disbursements pertaining to current and continuing projects were accounted and reported in the related documents to be able to present the correct amounts of the unexpended balances of LDRRMF at year-end.

We recommended that the BAC: 

ensure strict compliance with the requirements prescribed under the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 to prevent the same lapses in future procurements;

carefully prepare the Bidding Documents to be able to provide complete and accurate information to the prospective bidders in the preparation of bid proposal;

ensure that the information contained in the documents/ reports being prepared were consistent;

carefully check the additional documents submitted by the winning bidder which will form part of the contract to achieve consistency of information; and

ensure the timely submission of the perfected contracts and the documents forming part thereof to the Audit Team in compliance with Item 3.1.1 of COA Circular No. 2009-001.

We recommended that Management should reconcile the effects of the disparity in the balance of Cash against the balance of Trust Liabilities in the Trust Fund by the following;

The Accounting Office should set aside time for the tracing of the increases and decreases in the accounts which may indicate the sources of the reconciling items since the time/year these major account classifications had indicated imbalances;
Prepare the working paper for the erroneous entries as source of the   corresponding adjusting entries ;
Review, finalize and record the adjusting entries to rectify the affected Trust Fund Cash and Liability accounts.
The Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant should come into agreement on the responsible and accountable utilization of Trust Funds. 
As required, the Municipality should always report the utilization of Trust Funds on a regular basis to enhance reconciliation and transparency with the grantor Agency to avoid errors in presentation

We recommended that Management should-
For cash advances of deceased AOs-
Prepare the format for Request for Write Off of Cash Advance;
Offer them to be accomplished by relatives or heirs;
Request a copy of the Death Certificate to be used as attachment;
Indorse the Request for Write Off to the COA for proper evaluation whether to grant or deny the Request;
For cash advances of transferred, no longer be traced and terminated AOs-
Exert all efforts to determine and locate their new employers/ current addresses;
Serve Demand Letter and ask their commitment to pay by agreeing on the dates these refunds shall be collected by the Municipal Treasurer;
Assist them accomplish documents in case liquidation is through the submission of liquidation documents;
Pursue visitations until full liquidation is attained.

We recommended that Management –
Through the Inventory Committee, identify and segregate for disposal all unserviceable and obsolete properties of the municipality which could not be anymore useful to operations;
Through the information from the ledgers of the Accountant, earmark fully depreciated vehicles and equipment which are possible choices for disposal;
Determine the appraised value of properties for disposal still found valuable;
Prepare and submit the IIRUP and supporting documents for inspection;
Proceed to the appropriate procedures for the selected mode of disposal upon the advice/ signal of the Auditor;
 Account for all sales proceeds that should be taken up in the municipal books.
In the meantime that disposal could not yet be made, secure the subject unserviceable PPEs from harmful elements and from possible loss of parts through theft to protect the best interest of the Municipality.

We recommended to Management that-
The Sangguniang Bayan should engage due discretion in the crafting of legislative enactments and consider their real intent whether to issue a resolution or enact an ordinance;
The Sangguniang Bayan should engage due diligence and care  in the preparation of realignment of funds by attaching the salient requirements such as the certification under oath jointly by the accountant and treasurer, as well as the attestation of the Mayor;
The Municipality is advised to refrain from further disbursement from the realigned funds of P4,500,000.00 for being unauthorized use of government money.

We recommended that Management should-
Prepare checklist of sufficient and relevant documentary requirements for each nature/ kind of transaction by the Municipal Accountant as a salient attachment to all vouchers and payrolls;
Prepare flow chart of the disbursement procedure to be posted at the offices of the Budget Officer, Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer for the guidance of all officials and employees;
 For conflicts arising from inconsistencies observed in existing municipal procedures, Management should confer on the proper steps to be followed based on the provisions of the Government Accounting Manual for Local Government Units
Follow proper disbursement procedures by submitting complete documentary requirements to transactions to prevent the issuance of the Notice of Suspension.

We recommended that Management –
Conduct annual physical count of municipal properties;
prepare and submit the corresponding Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment by the designated Property Inventory Committee by indicating also therein the cost of the items and the persons in charge of properties and their respective offices to pinpoint accountability;  
reconcile the inventory report (RPCPPE) with the accounting records;  
book-up donated PPE in accordance with the Memorandum of Agreement or Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment, as the case may be which was executed  by the donor agency;  
segregate unserviceable items beyond repair and report them in the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Properties (IIRUP) so that the PPE accounts are properly accounted in the financial statements and unserviceable items are disposed within the limits of authority/Sangguniang Bayan resolution; and
identify lost items and prepare and file request for relief from accountability;
the preparation of the RPCPPE is a serious matter because it concerns the validation of the existence of the ownership over all municipal properties, thus, enforce the suspension of the payment of salaries of persons concerned who failed to prepare the required report until they have submitted said report to COA in consonance with Section 122 (1) of PD No. 1445.

We recommended that Management, particularly the Municipal Treasurer, strengthen internal control on collections, remittances and deposits by –

Putting into writing internal control procedures on collections, remittances and deposits to prevent delayed remittances and long period collections are held by collectors, such as –

Cut-off time for the submission of all reports of collections with the report of accountability for accountable forms (RAAF) (page 1 and 2) for the day is until 12:00 P.M. all collections afterwards shall be remitted before the same cut-off time of the following day, thereby no collection for the day shall be omitted in remittance for that day regardless of the quantity of accountable forms to be remitted, and the negligent collector shall submit his/her explanation for his failure to comply;

The Liquidating Officer shall receive all reports of collections and RAAF of the day until 12:00 PM, and shall immediately record them in her cashbook during the day and the morning of the following day when she shall immediately account for all collections she received and prepare the corresponding over-all Report of Collections and the cash or check deposit slips for all collections for the day to be deposited to the Authorized Government Depository Bank not later than the afternoon of the following day these collections were received. She shall prepare the proper authorization to travel to the AGDB;

Prepare a format to account for daily cash ticket issuances. Remit cash tickets on the day these were issued and collected. Stop the previous practice of accumulating  collections and remitting them only depending on the collector’s judgement. 

The Liquidating Officer shall transmit daily all her collections and the over-all Report of Collections with the corresponding deposit slips to the Municipal Accountant who shall prepare the  Abstract of Collections which shall summarize the accounts collected;

The Municipal Accountant shall prepare the Journal Entry Voucher for daily collections and deposits and posts them in the Journal of Collections and Deposits;

At the end of the month, the Liquidating Officer shall prepare the monthly RAAF which is reconciled with the issued accountable forms for the month and the balance of accountable forms with the actual accountable forms at her custody and at the custody of the collectors of the MTO; 

The Municipal Treasurer shall prepare the Monthly Report of Collections-Form 60 which is reconciled with the Abstract of Collections prepared by the Municipal Accountant. 

Require the barangay treasurers to remit all CTC collections of the month at the end of the month for proper accounting regardless of the quantity of issued CTCs to reduce the period these are held at the barangay coffers to prevent misuse.

We recommended that Management give more intense efforts to collect real property tax by-

Establishing the true amount of RPT collectibles net of problematic lands which shall be sourced from the combined efforts of the Municipal Assessor, Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant. The final RPT receivable amount to be set-up per year based on eligible properties shall be properly determined in order to fix the yearly receivable with some necessary minor modifications, if any, in the succeeding years in order to avoid excessive targets which could not be probably collected and cause the accumulation of huge amount of RPT receivables in the financial statements which might be misunderstood by the FS user as Management being grossly negligent in its fiscal function;
Utilizing the summer job trainees to aid in the conduct of information dissemination and collection campaign;
The continued efforts of the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the GF and SEF real property tax receivables by pinpointing inconsistent transactions affecting these accounts and making the necessary adjustments;
Strategizing early collection of RPT receivables by offering greater discount percentage if collection is done before the beginning of the fiscal year and a lesser rate before the  end of the no-penalty payment period;
If applicable, encourage installment payment of real property tax to take advantage of the funds of the taxpayer which is available at the time the collectors are dispersed in the barangay. Noting that the Filipino is “kuripot” but also enjoys paying installment in small amounts to the “Bombays” is an observation on the peculiarities of Filipino fund management that the Municipal Treasurer should understand and should take the necessary scheme to the advantage of the Municipality;
Also coordinating concerned municipal offices to create livelihood programs for the delinquent taxpayers as beneficiaries by utilizing their idle lands to be developed and become productive and can provide income as a source of payment for real property tax;
Institute the necessary civil and judicial remedies if all efforts to persuade and make productive the adamant taxpayers fail.

We recommended that  –

The departments concerned separate from their year-round programs for the 20% DF the non-capital outlay components and prepare separate program to be  charged  from the corresponding office appropriations in the General Fund;
Totally stop the charging of all soft projects and maintenance services against the  20% DF and ensure that all disbursements from the 20% Development Fund should contribute to the construction and acquisition of capital outlay development projects as stated in the JMC 2017-1;
Return back to the 20%DF all misused funds which were paid for maintenance services and soft projects and prepare another priority development program/s for this total amount;
Establish a monitoring committee to inspect and certify on the extent of percentage of completion of all development projects as necessary attachment to the vouchers of all disbursements from the 20% DF;Prepare as attachment to all 20% DF disbursement vouchers the details of disbursements from each of the development programs in a chronological sequence ending with the current voucher and properly totaled as to gross amount, tax withheld, if any, and the net amount including the name of payee and the particulars. This is to monitor if the amount of programmed expenses is sufficient to meet the actual claims for payment, otherwise, the actual spending should be adjusted to suffice the amount of appropriation for the program.

We recommended that Management –
Exert efforts to update the database containing gender statistics and sex-disaggregated data;
Identify priority PPAs based on the updated database considering the basic needs of each classification particularly women, children, elderly and men;
Incorporate the identified priority PPAs in the GAD plan/ update the GAD Plan;
Update the AIP;
Prepare the plan to implement these PPAs through PERT CPM  per stage to facilitate monitoring; 
Coordinate manpower efforts to pursue plans based on ability, participation and contribution;
Monitor and report weekly and monthly progress/development to emphasize the importance of GAD projects in the wholesome empowerment and development of each member of the community regardless of age and sex.

